<poem>
    <title poet="Bontemps_A">Length of the Moon</title>
    <stanza>
        <l n="1">Then the golden hour </l>
        <l n="2"><figLang form="personification">Will tick its last </figLang></l>
        <l n="3">And the flame will go down in the flower<punc type="period">.</punc></l>
        <l n="4">A briefer length of moon</l>
        <l n="5">Will mark the sea-line and the yellow dune<punc type="period">.</punc></l>
        <l n="6">Then we may think of this<punc type="comma">,</punc> yet </l>
        <l n="7">There will be something forgotten</l>
        <l n="8">It will be like all things we know<punc type="colon">:</punc></l>
        <l n="9"><figLang form="personification">A stone will fail</figLang><punc type="semicolon">;</punc> a rose is sure to go<punc type="period">.</punc></l>
        <l n="10">It will be quiet then and we may stay long at the picket gate</l>
        <l n="11">But there will be less to say<punc type="period">.</punc></l>
        
    </stanza>
</poem>
